upported by Chimiak et al. 2024 but with significantly lower yields (<3% initially, though 97% was mineral-bound). The in situ reduction of NO\u2083\u207b to NH\u2083 on ferroan brucite before reductive amination is a key bottleneck noted in the literature. The pathway is prebiotically relevant for post-GOE or photochemically-generated nitrate scenarios. Single-step, single-environment limitation as in P3.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Note the timescale limitation (weeks in lab experiments) as a potential issue for dynamic hydrothermal environments\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.93\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.89,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.86,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.90,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n      \"feedback\": \"Excellent convergent pathway building glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde via formose chemistry, then photooxidizing to glyoxylate, then reductive amination to glycine. The formose step (rxn_014) is well-known but often produces complex mixtures; specificity for glycolaldehyde requires careful conditions (e.g., mineral catalysis, dilute formaldehyde). rxn_012 (photooxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate) is the weakest link\u2014plausible under UV but less experimentally documented for this specific transformation. The Surface\u2192Surface\u2192Hydrothermal environmental flow is well-justified. This pathway gives full provenance for glyoxylate, addressing the sourcing gap in P3.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Cite specific photooxidation conditions or mineral photocatalysts for rxn_012 (e.g., TiO\u2082 analogues, iron oxide surfaces)\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.86\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.84,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n      \"feedback\": \"Parallel to P5 but using nitrate as the nitrogen source. Same strengths and weaknesses as P5, compounded by the lower yields of the nitrate pathway. The combination of formose chemistry, photooxidation, and nitrate reductive amination creates a plausible multi-environment route. The reliance on rxn_012 remains the weakest point.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Consider whether combined P5+P6 operating in parallel is more realistic than either alone\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.83\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.81,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.83,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.84,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n      \"feedback\": \"Creative pathway that sources ethanolamine from glycolaldehyde, solving the orphan intermediate problem identified in the strategy. rxn_013 (reductive amination of glycolaldehyde to ethanolamine) is plausible but less well-documented experimentally\u2014needs explicit reducing agent or mineral electron donor. rxn_008 is well-supported by Zhang et al. 2017 but should specify Fe/Co/Ni/Cu catalysts and high-temperature alkaline conditions. The Surface\u2192Hydrothermal\u2192Hydrothermal flow is reasonable. The H\u2082 byproduct in rxn_008 is debatable\u2014the oxidation mechanism likely involves metal-catalyzed dehydrogenation but the exact byproducts depend on the oxidant.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Specify reducing agent for rxn_013 (e.g., Fe\u00b2\u207a on mineral surface)\", \"Add metal catalyst specification to rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.82\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.84,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.81,\n      \"feedback\": \"Supported by Mates-Torres & Rimola (2026) computational study showing low-barrier glycine formation from H\u2082CO+CO+NH\u2083 on forsterite. Currently only computational evidence (no experimental verification). The single-step, single-environment pathway is simple but lacks provenance for precursors. Forsterite is correctly specified as the mineral surface. The Surface label is appropriate for grain-surface catalysis. This pathway is most relevant for warm interstellar/protoplanetary conditions but could also apply to weathered ultramafic rocks on early Earth.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Note this route is computationally supported but awaits experimental verification\", \"Could be strengthened by connecting CO and NH\u2083 sourcing from hydrothermal reactions\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.87,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.86,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.89,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.87,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n      \"feedback\": \"Elegant convergent pathway: formaldimine (from CH\u2082O+NH\u2083 on surface) and formate (from CO\u2082+H\u2082 at hydrothermal vents on greigite) combine to form glycine. Well-supported by Xu et al. 2024 which highlights formaldimine as a more reactive intermediate than HCN. The convergence from two different environments is a strength. rxn_010 (condensation) is straightforward. rxn_001 (CO\u2082 hydrogenation on greigite) is supported by submarine vent chemistry. rxn_011 (formaldimine-formate coupling) has moderate barriers (~40-50 kcal/mol per Xu et al.) but is computationally validated. Good Hydrothermal+Surface\u2192Surface flow.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Consider whether the ~40-50 kcal/mol barrier for rxn_011 is accessible under surface conditions without additional catalysis\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.87,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n      \"feedback\": \"Alternative formaldimine sourcing via HCN partial hydrogenation on mackinawite (rxn_016). This is the least experimentally documented reaction in the network\u2014partial hydrogenation of HCN to CH\u2082=NH on FeS is chemically plausible (FeS is a known hydrogenation catalyst) but specific experimental evidence is sparse. The Hydrothermal\u2192Hydrothermal\u2192Surface flow is well-structured. The convergence with formate (rxn_001) at the surface coupling step (rxn_011) mirrors P9 nicely. Mackinawite specification is appropriate for early Earth hydrothermal vents.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Seek experimental support for HCN\u2192formaldimine on mackinawite\", \"This pathway could be strengthened if HCN sourcing from rxn_003 were explicitly linked\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.89,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is an exceptionally well-designed convergent synthesis network for prebiotic glycine. The netw